d from the SeaWiFS sensor with AERONET data over Bermuda and Wallops Island show very good agreement with one another. In fact, 81\% of the data points over Bermuda and 78\% of the data points over Wallops Island fall within an uncertainty of {\textpm}0.02 in optical thickness. As a part of the reprocessing effort of the SeaWiFS data, we also revised the vicarious calibration gain factors, which resulted in significant improvement in angstrom coefficient ($\alpha$) retrievals. The average value of $\alpha$ from the new models over Bermuda is 0.841{\textpm}0.171, which is in good agreement with the AERONET value of 0.891{\textpm}0.211. The average value of $\alpha$ retrieved using old models is 0.394{\textpm}0.087, which is significantly lower than the AERONET value.},
